         <h1>Barney Simon, 63, Producer; Used Art to Fight Apartheid </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Barney Simon , a leader in South African theater and an imaginative thorn in the side of the authorities during the apartheid years , died on Friday at Milpark Hospital here . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 63 . <br><blue>3</blue>Mr. Simon , who had undergone heart bypass surgery two weeks ago , died of a pulmonary embolism , said Hillary Hamburger , a friend who drove him to the hospital on Wednesday . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Simon was a founder in 1976 of the pioneering Market Theater , a bustling complex occupying part of a defunct Indian produce market that became South Africa 's only theater with an international reputation . <br><blue>5</blue>He is best remembered for defying the law and producing works by writers who attacked the hypocrisy of apartheid and for running a theater where blacks and whites shared the stage and performed for multiracial audiences . <br><blue>6</blue>Mr. Simon 's name was not as familiar in the United States as those of Athol Fugard or Nadine Gordimer -- although he directed Mr. Fugard 's plays and film versions of some of Ms. Gordimer 's novels -- but he was the moving force of dissident theater in South Africa . <br><blue>7</blue>Before he acquired the Market Theater in 1976 , he staged multi-racial plays anywhere he could : in warehouses and shantytowns , storefronts and backyards . <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Fugard , who worked with Mr. Simon for 37 years , recalled today : " I remember Barney pasting cardboard egg crates to the windows of a little attic for soundproofing because we were competing with a tribal dance from a mine compound next door . <br><blue>9</blue>I ca n't think of a single young playwright or actor , white or black , who is n't indebted to Barney . <br><blue>10</blue>And that includes an old warhorse like myself . " <br><blue>11</blue>Mr. Simon loved the theater as much as he loved tweaking the authorities , and he threw himself into every aspect of his work . <br><blue>12</blue>His friends recalled today a time when he staged a play in the backyard of a dissident under house arrest so the man could watch it out the window , and another incident when he posed as a headwaiter in a restaurant next door to a performance space to hush up the noisy diner whose complaints were drowning out his production of " Antigone . " <br><blue>13</blue>During the worst years of apartheid , the Market Theater was one of the few places where whites and blacks could mix on equal terms ; in a world of legislated abnormality , it was a reminder of civil standards of behavior . <br><blue>14</blue>In the 1980 's it became , in effect , an exporter of black opposition theater , with Mr. Fugard 's plays , Mbongeni Ngema 's " Sarafina ! <br><blue>15</blue>, " and " Woza Albert ! " <br><blue>16</blue>-- by Mr. Ngema and Percy Mtwa in collaboration with Mr. Simon -- among the best examples . <br><blue>17</blue>" South Africa is an appalling place in an appalling world , " Mr. Simon said in a 1984 interview . <br><blue>18</blue>" I have friends who have been arrested . <br><blue>19</blue>I have friends who have been blown up . <br><blue>20</blue>One is surrounded by these grotesque biographies . <br><hr><br><blue>1(1)</blue>: <m_str>his work</m_str> (11_23) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>the law</m_str> (5_7) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Fugard 's plays</m_str> (6_25) 	<m_str>Mr. Fugard 's plays</m_str> (14_19) 	<br><blue>4(1)</blue>: <m_str>an appalling world</m_str> (17_9) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Ngema</m_str> (16_3) 	<m_str>Mbongeni Ngema 's</m_str> (14_24) 	<br><blue>6(2)</blue>: <m_str>a single young playwright or actor , white or black , who is n't indebted to Barney</m_str> (9_6) 	<m_str>that</m_str> (10_2) 	<br><blue>7(7)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Fugard 's</m_str> (6_25) 	<m_str>myself</m_str> (10_8) 	<m_str>Mr. Fugard 's</m_str> (14_19) 	<m_str>Athol Fugard</m_str> (6_16) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (8_17) 	<m_str>Mr. Fugard , who worked with Mr. Simon for 37 years</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (9_1) 	<br><blue>8(5)</blue>: <m_str>the theater</m_str> (11_4) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (14_5) 	<m_str>the Market Theater</m_str> (13_8) 	<m_str>the Market Theater</m_str> (7_4) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (13_34) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>it</m_str> (12_26) 	<m_str>a play</m_str> (12_10) 	<br><blue>10(2)</blue>: <m_str>Nadine Gordimer</m_str> (6_19) 	<m_str>Ms. Gordimer 's</m_str> (6_35) 	<br><blue>11(24)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (7_10) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (11_9) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Simon</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_15) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_60) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (11_16) 	<m_str>himself</m_str> (11_18) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (3_28) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_41) 	<m_str>Mr. Simon</m_str> (8_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_23) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_8) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Simon</m_str> (16_11) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Simon 's</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_35) 	<m_str>Mr. Simon</m_str> (17_14) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (18_2) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_2) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_23) 	<m_str>Mr. Simon</m_str> (11_1) 	<br><blue>12(2)</blue>: <m_str>1976</m_str> (4_7) 	<m_str>1976</m_str> (7_8) 	<br><blue>13(3)</blue>: <m_str>South Africa 's</m_str> (4_27) 	<m_str>South Africa</m_str> (17_2) 	<m_str>South Africa</m_str> (6_50) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:african<br>         </p>
